34
00:01:46,833 --> 00:01:49,733
first, let's cover the basics of particles in GTNH

35
00:01:50,366 --> 00:01:52,500
particles in beams travel as packets

36
00:01:52,900 --> 00:01:55,333
similar to the research station computation packets

37
00:01:55,733 --> 00:01:58,033
particle packets have four attributes

38
00:01:58,033 --> 00:02:00,066
type, energy, amount and focus

39
00:02:00,466 --> 00:02:01,733
type is the type of particle

40
00:02:01,733 --> 00:02:04,100
so electron, muon, photon and so on

41
00:02:04,266 --> 00:02:06,766
energy is the energy of the particle in electron volts

42
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:14,566
amount which is sometimes sort of inconsistently called rate here and there can be interpreted as the number of individual particles in the packet

43
00:02:14,700 --> 00:02:17,366
this is what determines crafting speed in the beamcrafter

44
00:02:17,366 --> 00:02:19,266
and is the quantity you want to maximize

45
00:02:19,566 --> 00:02:22,366
focus is not relevant for the LHC and beamcrafting

46
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:25,733
but it's a quantity that represents the collimation of the beam

47
00:02:25,733 --> 00:02:26,966
this matters for beamline

48
00:02:26,966 --> 00:02:29,266
but we will completely ignore it in this video

49
00:02:29,266 --> 00:02:31,700
next, let's talk about how the LHC actually works

50
00:02:32,133 --> 00:02:35,366
I will continue based on the assumption that you have read the tooltip for details

51
00:02:35,566 --> 00:02:38,500
the LHC takes any charged particle as input

52
00:02:38,866 --> 00:02:41,000
and generates output depending on:

53
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,366
1. the energy of the collision and 2. which module you draw outputs from

54
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:48,566
the LHC has two modes accelerator and collider

55
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:50,166
it cycles once per second

56
00:02:50,166 --> 00:02:55,533
and automatically switches from accelerator to collider when the player set acceleration cycle count is reached

57
00:02:55,900 --> 00:02:56,766
in the interface

58
00:02:56,766 --> 00:02:58,000
if you click this button

59
00:02:58,066 --> 00:02:59,733
you are able to set two values

60
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:02,966
the target beam energy and the acceleration cycle count

61
00:03:03,266 --> 00:03:05,400
once you set these and turn on the LHC

62
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:07,666
it will start accelerating the incoming beam

63
00:03:08,100 --> 00:03:12,533
this input beam cannot have any of its four parameters change during operation

64
00:03:12,533 --> 00:03:14,133
or the LHC will shut down

65
00:03:14,266 --> 00:03:16,733
using the incoming beam's values as the starting point

66
00:03:16,900 --> 00:03:19,900
the LHC will accelerate the beam in accelerator mode

67
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:22,700
meaning the beam energy increases once per cycle

68
00:03:22,733 --> 00:03:25,600
if the beam energy reaches the player set target energy

69
00:03:25,966 --> 00:03:29,266
further LHC cycles will instead increase the current beam amount

70
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:31,500
but how do you know what target energy to set

71
00:03:32,066 --> 00:03:34,266
well, the beam energy serves one purpose

72
00:03:34,566 --> 00:03:37,166
adding particle types to the pool of potential outputs

73
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:39,866
if you have an accelerated beam energy of E

74
00:03:39,966 --> 00:03:42,966
then the collision energy when particles collide is 2 times E

75
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,566
the types of particles that can appear in the outputs now are simply all those particles whose mass is 2E or lower

76
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,466
so if you're targeting a particle of mass 100 giga electron volts

77
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:55,666
then set your target energy to at least 50 giga electron volts

78
00:03:55,666 --> 00:03:56,800
then the collision is 100

79
00:03:56,800 --> 00:03:58,100
and you can get these particles

80
00:03:58,366 --> 00:04:01,566
there's no benefit to increasing energy beyond what you need

81
00:04:01,566 --> 00:04:04,066
also, not all particles can appear in all modules

82
00:04:04,666 --> 00:04:07,666
each LHC module can only produce a subset of particles

83
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:08,933
you can see this in NEI

84
00:04:08,933 --> 00:04:11,200
the power draw of the LHC can be very high

85
00:04:11,266 --> 00:04:13,133
since it increases quadratically with time

86
00:04:13,133 --> 00:04:15,033
and it also scales with beam amount

87
00:04:15,033 --> 00:04:20,733
that said, I have done an analysis of how the resulting crafting speed in the beam crafter scales with the power draw

88
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,800
and I found that it's best to do as many cycles as possible

89
00:04:24,266 --> 00:04:25,733
the more cycles you do the closer

90
00:04:25,733 --> 00:04:27,166
you get to perfect overclocking

91
00:04:27,766 --> 00:04:31,833
details of this analysis are in an optional advanced section later in the video

92
00:04:31,833 --> 00:04:32,766
OK, that was a lot

93
00:04:33,133 --> 00:04:34,766
let's talk about how to use these particles

94
00:04:34,933 --> 00:04:38,500
the Beamcrafter is a multi that takes fluid, item and particle inputs

95
00:04:38,766 --> 00:04:41,666
the craft begins as soon as input items and fluids are detected

96
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:43,800
the machine then waits for particle inputs

97
00:04:43,800 --> 00:04:45,466
which provide progress to the craft

98
00:04:45,766 --> 00:04:47,400
no particles means no progress

99
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:50,566
the recipe does not shut down if the particle beams are interrupted

100
00:04:50,966 --> 00:04:54,300
NEI shows the cumulative beam amounts required for the crafts

101
00:04:54,566 --> 00:04:57,666
and energy is consumed constantly while the craft is going

102
00:04:57,933 --> 00:05:02,266
note that at the time of recording the beamcrafter does not work with the crafting input buses of buffers

103
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:05,366
you don't really need them though since there's not that many recipes

104
00:05:05,366 --> 00:05:08,600
and your processing is going to be limited by the LHC rates anyway

105
00:05:09,100 --> 00:05:11,000
also the Beamcrafter can buffer particles

106
00:05:11,166 --> 00:05:14,500
but it's only able to accept particles while a recipe is running

107
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:18,300
this may be changed to allow constant buffering at all times

108
00:05:18,366 --> 00:05:20,266
but for now this is how it's going to be

109
00:05:20,533 --> 00:05:22,700
just gonna quickly mention these because they exist

110
00:05:22,966 --> 00:05:25,900
but they're all fairly easy to understand by reading the tooltips

111
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:30,600
the Beam Mirror allows you to turn a particle beam by 90 or 180 degrees

112
00:05:30,966 --> 00:05:33,366
the Beam Stabilizer acts as a small buffer

113
00:05:33,466 --> 00:05:37,400
allowing you to make an intermittent beam of high amount a constant beam of low amount

114
00:05:37,700 --> 00:05:43,100
and the Beam Splitter allows you to split a mixed stream of particle packets into four separate configurable lines

115
00:05:44,266 --> 00:05:47,300
OK, and here's a little bit of fun stuff for the nerds in here

116
00:05:47,366 --> 00:05:48,466
I know you're out there

117
00:05:48,566 --> 00:05:52,333
I said before that the LHC overclocking is a bit weird

118
00:05:52,366 --> 00:05:54,766
and it's kind of its own thing, so

119
00:05:55,300 --> 00:05:57,766
if you're interested in finding out how it actually works

120
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:59,000
this is how it works

121
00:05:59,166 --> 00:06:00,300
we've got two equations

122
00:06:00,533 --> 00:06:02,400
R equals R0 a to the N

123
00:06:02,700 --> 00:06:04,566
and P equals R N squared

124
00:06:05,266 --> 00:06:06,900
R is the accelerated rate

125
00:06:06,933 --> 00:06:09,900
the rate with which you do collisions in the LHC

126
00:06:10,666 --> 00:06:12,300
R0 is the initial rate

127
00:06:12,333 --> 00:06:13,300
the input rate

128
00:06:13,466 --> 00:06:15,066
a is the multiplication factor

129
00:06:15,066 --> 00:06:16,900
which currently is 1.1

130
00:06:16,900 --> 00:06:18,933
but that might be changed for balancing reasons

131
00:06:18,933 --> 00:06:20,300
so I've just left it as a

132
00:06:20,500 --> 00:06:21,500
N is the cycle count

133
00:06:21,500 --> 00:06:24,133
and P is the power draw in amps of UV

134
00:06:24,133 --> 00:06:25,166
in these two equations

135
00:06:25,500 --> 00:06:27,733
you can solve for N in the bottom one

136
00:06:27,733 --> 00:06:29,500
and plug it into the equation in the top

137
00:06:29,666 --> 00:06:31,300
and then after a bit of simplification

138
00:06:31,700 --> 00:06:34,500
you get the base relationship which is this

139
00:06:34,766 --> 00:06:35,566
pretty ugly

140
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:38,166
there's not really much I can say with just this equation

141
00:06:38,333 --> 00:06:39,533
so we ask the question

142
00:06:39,666 --> 00:06:41,666
what happens if we overclock

143
00:06:42,066 --> 00:06:45,366
remember that R determines crafting speed in the beam crafter

144
00:06:45,366 --> 00:06:46,400
and P is the power

145
00:06:46,600 --> 00:06:50,566
you can't really overclock the LHC by increasing the energy hatch

146
00:06:50,566 --> 00:06:54,900
what I mean by overclock in this case is running more cycles because the power draw is going to increase

147
00:06:54,900 --> 00:07:00,500
so the question becomes what happens if you run enough cycles that the power draw has increased by a factor of 4

148
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:01,400
in other words

149
00:07:01,733 --> 00:07:04,700
if P becomes 4P, then what happens to rate

150
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:08,133
and I declare that R becomes k times R

151
00:07:08,166 --> 00:07:09,466
the question is what is k

152
00:07:09,800 --> 00:07:11,266
for a normal multiblock

153
00:07:11,466 --> 00:07:16,333
k is equal to 4 or k is equal to 2 if it's perfectly overclocking or if it's not perfectly overclocking

154
00:07:16,866 --> 00:07:18,500
but in the LHC case

155
00:07:18,533 --> 00:07:20,133
it's a little more weird

156
00:07:20,200 --> 00:07:24,766
so we transform P to 4P and we transform R to kR in the base relationship

157
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:26,800
and then we get the overclocked relationship

158
00:07:27,366 --> 00:07:32,166
which is basically the same thing but P has become 4P and R has become kR

159
00:07:32,200 --> 00:07:34,400
this still isn't really enough to say anything

160
00:07:34,766 --> 00:07:37,466
so what we need to do is compare the two relationships

161
00:07:37,500 --> 00:07:43,733
we compare the overclocked relationship with the base relationship by taking the ratios of the left hand sides and the right hand sides

162
00:07:44,166 --> 00:07:45,533
we get this equation

163
00:07:46,066 --> 00:07:47,466
after a bit of simplification

164
00:07:47,566 --> 00:07:49,133
a lot of stuff cancels out

165
00:07:49,266 --> 00:07:51,900
and we just get a relationship between k and R

166
00:07:52,133 --> 00:07:54,166
you can try to solve for k

167
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:56,466
but it's not gonna work

168
00:07:56,700 --> 00:07:58,300
you need a Lambert function and stuff

169
00:07:58,300 --> 00:07:59,333
it's not worth your time

170
00:07:59,400 --> 00:08:00,966
so just plot this implicitly

171
00:08:01,066 --> 00:08:02,466
and then we can draw some conclusions

172
00:08:02,500 --> 00:08:08,000
this is the plot where y is k and x is R over R0

173
00:08:08,300 --> 00:08:09,566
and as you can see

174
00:08:09,566 --> 00:08:10,900
it is very weird

175
00:08:11,700 --> 00:08:17,200
keep in mind that normal multiblocks just have a constant y equals 2 or y equals 4 line

176
00:08:17,666 --> 00:08:22,133
but the LHC has something that changes with time basically

177
00:08:22,266 --> 00:08:25,400
as you run more cycles, the overclocking factor improves

178
00:08:25,600 --> 00:08:28,433
and in fact it's worse than a regular overclock

179
00:08:28,433 --> 00:08:32,666
until you get to about five times the beam rate that you started with

180
00:08:33,133 --> 00:08:34,600
after that it's as good as a regular

181
00:08:34,600 --> 00:08:37,600
and then it continues to increase, but not forever

182
00:08:37,600 --> 00:08:39,733
it asymptotes to a perfect overclock

183
00:08:39,966 --> 00:08:42,500
I tried to zoom out a bit here but it's really not obvious

184
00:08:42,500 --> 00:08:44,500
you have to do a lot of cycles

185
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:48,866
like an unbelievable number of cycles to actually get to a perfect overclock

186
00:08:48,866 --> 00:08:50,900
adjacent overclock factor

187
00:08:51,066 --> 00:08:53,100
this is something I may tweak as well

188
00:08:53,300 --> 00:08:54,400
because I have ...

189
00:08:54,400 --> 00:08:58,066
actually this is a homework exercise for you if you're interested

190
00:08:58,366 --> 00:08:59,866
let me let me state the problem clearly

191
00:09:00,366 --> 00:09:01,966
introduce a constant c

192
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:03,966
which is a tunable parameter

193
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:04,966
which I can set

194
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:11,066
which determines the asymptotic value of the overclock in the large R over R0 limit

195
00:09:11,466 --> 00:09:17,766
basically find a new equation or a new pair of equations that lets me choose what the asymptote is

196
00:09:17,900 --> 00:09:20,066
the equations I have right now asymptote to four

197
00:09:20,733 --> 00:09:23,400
but if I wanted to asymptote to 16 or something

198
00:09:23,933 --> 00:09:25,600
what would the equations have to be

199
00:09:25,933 --> 00:09:27,133
that's a fun little question

200
00:09:27,300 --> 00:09:28,133
it's kind of hard

201
00:09:28,300 --> 00:09:29,466
but I figured it out

202
00:09:29,466 --> 00:09:31,200
and it's really really ugly

203
00:09:31,866 --> 00:09:32,666
here's the answer

204
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:33,700
spoiler alert

205
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:36,466
it's really ugly

206
00:09:36,466 --> 00:09:38,000
anyway that's my analysis

207
00:09:39,133 --> 00:09:40,933
I hope you found this guide helpful

208
00:09:41,200 --> 00:09:43,366
and I hope you enjoy the LHC

209
00:09:43,900 --> 00:09:45,566
and if it's not fun let me know

210
00:09:45,566 --> 00:09:48,866
and I am more than happy to change how it works so that it is fun

211
00:09:48,933 --> 00:09:51,566
that is the most important thing, even more than realism

212
00:09:51,700 --> 00:09:53,733
as much as it hurts me to say

213
00:09:53,733 --> 00:09:54,666
anyway, enjoy

